    <text>
        <body><div type="bibliography">
                
            <p><bibl><ptr target="#IGCyr"/> <citedRange>029350</citedRange></bibl>.
                Cf. <bibl><ptr target="#thorn2005"/>, p. 422, n. <citedRange>i</citedRange> and fig. 257</bibl> (mention and drawing);
                    <bibl><ptr target="#dthorn-thorn2009"/>, p. <citedRange>91</citedRange></bibl>.
                </p>
            </div><div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
                
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><persName type="attested" key=""><name nymRef="#Εὐρυκλείδας">Εὐκλείδα<supplied reason="lost">ς</supplied></name>
                    <lb n="2"/><persName type="attested" key=""><name nymRef="#Εὖφρις">Εὔφριος</name></persName></persName>
	 </ab>
            </div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                <p/>
            </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="fr" xml:space="preserve">
            <p>Eukleidas fils d'Euphris.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="en" xml:space="preserve">
            <p>Eukleidas son of Euphris.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="it" xml:space="preserve">
            <p>Eukleidas figlio di Euphris.</p>
         </div><div type="commentary">
                
               <p>This stele was seen and drawn by Thorn above tomb N240 along with <ref type="inscription" source="#IGCyr2">IGCyr029300</ref>, the latter only having been 
               published by Ghislanzoni.</p>
	           <p>This sort of stele is thought by Thorn to have stood on top of a sarcophagus.</p>
	           <p/>
            </div></body>
    </text>
